'''Amy Welborn''' (born July 17, 1960, [[Bloomington, Indiana]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] writer and activist, as well as a public speaker. Formerly, she was a theology teacher at a Catholic high school in Lakeland Florida and served as a parish Director of Religious Education.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholics take a decidedly different view of 'Code' |author=Pinsky, Mark I. |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=2006-01-28 |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2006-01-28/news/DAVINCIBOX28_1_da-vinci-code-opus-dei-catholics |accessdate=2010-09-05}}</ref><ref name="II">{{cite web |title=Meeting The Real Mary Magdalene: An Interview with Amy Welborn |work=IgnatiusInsight.com |date=2006-05-12 |url=http://www.ignatiusinsight.com/features2006/awelborn_intvwmm_may06.asp |accessdate=2010-09-05}}</ref> She was a columnist for ''[[Our Sunday Visitor]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=De-coding Da Vinci: Zenit interviews Amy Welborn on her new book |work=[[Zenit News Agency]] |date=2004-04-07 |url=http://www.opusdei.us/art.php?p=7811 |accessdate=2010-09-06}}</ref> as well as for Catholic News Service.

==Blog==
Welborn was one of the first Catholic bloggers.<ref name="USA Today">{{cite web |title=Bloggers keep the faith, contentiously |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2007-11-27 |url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/religion/2007-11-26-faith-bloggers_N.htm |accessdate=2010-09-05}}</ref> She has changed her blog's name and server on three occasions. The four successive blogs have been In Between Naps (amywelborn.blogspot.com), Open Book (amywelborn.typepad.com), Charlotte Was Both (amywelborn.wordpress.com), and Via Media (blog.beliefnet.com/ViaMedia). Open Book received almost 12,000 page views per day when it was still active.<ref>{{cite web |title=God on the Internet. |author=V., Jonathan |work=[[TheFreeDictionary.com#TheFreeLibrary.com|TheFreeLibrary.com]] |publisher=First Things: A Monthly Journal of Religion and Public Life |date=2005-01-12 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/God+on+the+Internet-a0139206466 |accessdate=2010-09-06}}</ref> 

Welborn considers blogging to be an alternative venue to expose unpopular views.<ref>{{cite web |title=Catholics online: never an unpublished thought |work=Goliath |date=2002-11-08 |url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-2284183/Catholics-online-never-an-unpublished.html |accessdate=2010-09-05}}</ref>

==Education==
Welborn holds a BA in Honors History from the [[University of Tennessee]] and an MA in Church History from [[Vanderbilt Divinity School]].<ref name="II"/>



==Publications==
* ''De-Coding Da Vinci'', which examines the historical accuracy of [[Dan Brown]]'s novel ''[[The Da Vinci Code]]''.
* ''Here. Now. A Catholic Guide to the Good Life,'' targeted toward teens and young adults who have questions about [[Catholicism]] and [[faith]] in general.
* The ''Prove It'' [[apologetics]] series for young people, a five-book collection of questions and answers about God, the Church, Jesus, prayer and you.
* "A Catholic Woman's Book of Days" 
*  "The Loyola Kids' Book of Saints"
*  "The Loyola KIds' Book of Heroes"
*  "Friendship with Jesus: Pope Benedict XVI Talks to Children about their First Holy Communion"
*  "Be Saints! An Invitation from Pope Benedict XVI"
*  "Bambinelli Sunday:  A Christmas Blessing"

